1. Static member function
HelperClass has a static member function std::string get_data() which is never actually called. Static member functions are useful for providing common functionality to a class that is shared between all instances of the class. However, in this case, it is not used, and just occupies memory. This is generally frowned upon in C++ and is considered a code smell (code smell).
2. Dependent classes
The HelperClass class is dependent on the caller to provide its data. This is not good design. Ideally, the data should be consumed and not provided. In this case, the caller should be responsible for providing the data.

